Question: "What is the overriding objective?"
Good response: "The overriding objective is the fundamental principle that enables courts to deal with cases justly and at proportionate cost [1]. This principle encompasses several key elements that work together to ensure fair and efficient justice [1]. Central to this objective is ensuring that parties are on an equal footing and can participate fully in proceedings, allowing parties and witnesses to give their best evidence while managing costs effectively [1].

The court applies proportionality across multiple dimensions when implementing the overriding objective, considering the amount of money involved, the importance and complexity of the case, and the financial position of each party [1]. These considerations are balanced with the need for expeditious and fair case handling, while ensuring appropriate allocation of the court's resources among all cases [1]. The objective also promotes the use of alternative dispute resolution and enforces compliance with rules, practice directions and orders [1].

The courts must actively seek to give effect to this overriding objective when exercising any power under the Rules or interpreting any rule, subject to specific exceptions [2]. This duty extends to the parties themselves, who are required to help the court further the overriding objective [3]. Active case management by the court is essential to achieving these goals and includes encouraging cooperation between parties, identifying issues early, determining which issues require full investigation, and using technology and other tools to ensure trials proceed quickly and efficiently [4]."

Bad response (DO NOT WRITE LIKE THIS): "The overriding objective is to enable the court to deal with cases justly and at proportionate cost [1]. It includes ensuring parties are on equal footing [1]. It also includes saving expense [1]. It also includes dealing with cases proportionately [1]. It also includes ensuring cases are dealt with expeditiously [1]."

